Soil is a dynamic, heterogeneous, well-structured natural environment vital for the sustenance of living organisms, nutrient cycling, and neutralizing detrimental effects of harmful toxic pollutants. In recent times, the surge of industrialization, the emergence of modern agricultural practices, and various anthropogenic practices have led to the degradation of agricultural soil quality (Durdu et al., 2023). Many physical and chemical approaches have been proposed for the reclamation of such soils over the years. However, owing to their infeasibility and inefficiency under certain circumstances, a sustainable and environment-friendly strategy was needed to overcome the problem of soil erosion and infertile soil (Hou and Al-Tabbaa, 2014). The biological approach that harnesses the biofilm-forming ability of bacteria in remediating soil has received considerable attention globally. Thus, biofilm-forming bacteria have multifaceted applications in the sustainable remediation of different types of soils, including salt-affected soils, arid and semi-arid soils, fly ash polluted lands, and mine lands (Fig. 1
                     ). The biofilm-forming bacteria exhibit various mechanisms to remediate these different types of soil and promote sustainable soil management approaches (Table 1
                     ).

Gaseous emissions from anthropogenic and natural sources release harmful air pollutants into the environment. While outdoor pollution is primarily due to emissions from industrial and vehicular exhaust, indoor pollution is elevated by smoking and combustion activities such as cooking and open fires. Prolonged exposure to these indoor and outdoor air pollutants can cause various cardiovascular and pulmonary disorders in affected individuals (Leung, 2015; Pompilio and Di Bonaventura, 2020; GonzÃ¡lez-MartÃ­n et al., 2024). Recent studies highlighted that the rising concentrations of indoor VOCs have raised serious concerns among households because of their carcinogenic properties (Russell et al., 2014; Gonzalez-Martin et al., 2021). Among the various air pollution mitigation strategies, biofiltration using microbes is a widely used biological treatment method to control the emissions and carry out the transformation of air pollutants (Fig. 2
                     ). In these systems, the polluted gas is vented off through the porous packing material associated with the microbial biofilm layer. The soluble organic compounds get transferred to the surrounding aqueous medium to reach the biofilm, which is further degraded by microbial activity (Fulazzaky et al., 2014; Cheng et al., 2022; Sheoran et al., 2022). Application of bacterial biofilm-EPS in biofilters demonstrated high VOC removal efficiency, rendering bacterial biofilm as an appropriate mode for the purification of air pollutants (Estrada et al., 2013). Integration of bacterial biofilm into the bioreactors can offer an effective solution for the treatment of volatile air pollutants. Additionally, biofilters can also serve as a valuable tool for the treatment of waste and odorous gases such as nitrogen oxides (NOx) and sulfur oxides (SOx) (Wu et al., 2018). However, excessive adhesion of PM to biofilter may lead to their clogging. Furthermore, the application of the multispecies biofilm over biofilters might offer several advantages over single bacteria for the transformation of gaseous pollutants (Han et al., 2016; Xie et al., 2021; Pineda et al., 2023). Table 2
                      summarizes various mechanisms employed by bacterial biofilm to control the emission of air pollutants.
